>>115002134
Coming from someone who has learned DJing and done shows and has been learning production for three years, it's not comparable at all. It's going to take a lot more time to get better at production than learning how to mix that I can't recommend learning how to DJ unless you really have a passion for it. You're way better off learning how DAWs and synthesizers work if you want to produce UKG, the DJing can wait until later.

One of the only few positives I can think of when it comes to learning how to DJ from a production standpoint is that it forces you to listen to a lot of music which helps you develop your taste on what good and bad music is, but you should already be doing that if you're a fan of music. Beyond that it's good from a marketing standpoint, but that shouldn't matter until you become a real artist. Just pick up reaper and vital and go search on youtube for a few tutorials to get you started on your journey.

>>115025024
Different anon here. Any DAW will be intimidating the first time you open it if you've never used one before. You just have to power through some beginner's tutorials until you know how to:
>navigate the software's GUI
>configure your audio/MIDI drivers and settings
>record stuff (after arming the track and selecting the right inputs)
>use virtual instruments and edit MIDI
>add effects
>arrange clips on the timeline
>export your songs

Those are the main things to start with. It helps to break it all down into manageable topics instead of seeing "music production" as some huge mountain to climb all at once. Eventually, you'll also want to learn how to
>manage/organize the way you save files
>scan for 3rd party plugins
>use automation for different parameters
>learn keyboard shortcuts
>etc.

But once you get past the first list I wrote, you can just experiment and look up individual topics as you think of them. When I first started, it helped to keep a list of topics I wanted to learn as I thought of them. It always felt good to scratch off a whole page of stuff that used to baffle me. Hang in there anon, you got this.

>speed should be called rate

Yes. The two smaller knobs control an envelope that gets applied to the larger knob parameter to their left: the 'envelope' knob controls the shape of the envelope (attack is counterclockwise from the 0 position, decay is clockwise) as well as its strength, and the 'time' knob controls controls its attack/decay time.

>>115045604
The chorus is built around a progression from what amounts to a Caug played over a Cdim an octave lower that resolves to a relatively consonant A#m, followed by an E that moves to an F# which i thought felt unexpected, but then made sense in the transition back to Cdim. The high distorted choir sampler plays a melody i liked that mostly plays off the transition from the nasty first chord to the A#m. In the verse things are more complicated because i've got the bass moving between an F# and an F#m, but I'm vocoding it with a high band count using a vocal that normally ambles around in A# major, but sometimes I lower it by a major 3rd because it makes it sound really cool with the bass when it plays the F#m. I started out having em in the same key but that ended up sounding cooler probably cause of the parallel 3rds and so I kept it. I think the one super inept thing i need to fix is the little trumpet cause i put those notes in before i did the key change to the vocal and it sounds very confusing harmonically. Rhythmically I used triplets on the hat and 1 and 3 on the kick to establish a really consistent reference meter so i could fuck around with the snare a lot. I still hit the 4 but hit the & of 1 instead of 2, then i liked having a hit on the 2nd quarter note (idk why theory calls triplets quarter notes but whatever) of the & of 2, which I think is because it comes really close to being in the middle of the two other main snare hits but is meaningfully early, and to make the rhythm make sense i ended the loop with a cheeky double on the last two triplets. If i wanted to write a basic pop song off a 4 chord melody I probably could do a decent job, but that sounds really boring, so I wrote this instead, which uses significantly more complex theory. I didn't even get into all the chord extensions from the stacked instruments in the chorus.

>>115056373
I'd say for one a LOT of pausing/rewinding - and first off try to get the overall chords down one at a time. Play even just one note on your guitar or piano until it matches the chord and then find another note that matches, keep going until you have a complete triad or so

It was hard with the songs I mentioned because Brian Wilson will often combine chords, use many transitional chords (diminished etc), and he would often use a different note from a chord for the bass notes, throwing the overall perception of the chord off

(Example, in Caroline No or God Only Knows he'll put the 3rd of the minor chord as the root/bass, making the overall tonality of the chord appear to be a major 6th, but it's actually just a minor - leaving it somewhere vague and I think quite beautiful)

>>115056385
And personally with some Beach Boys I do have to re-remember the chords because they're so non-standard. But it is kind of different for me because I've always had a natural ear for just knowing a song's chords without often picking up an instrument (if it's not too complex)

It's not autism. It's just an appreciation for good music. Bad music is bad and good songs become bad when they're remastered poorly.
I don't care what they play in a grocery store or a mall but when I'm home or using my own equipment I want shit to sound good.

If this were audiophile autism we'd be bitching about YouTube compression and muh bitrates, but the fact is the difference between an original recording and a typical remaster is so large that bitrates and algorithms become irrelevant because it's a night/day difference and the remasters are usually worse.
Sometimes remasters are better, but those are rare, and any service that feeds remasters to users requesting original versions is unacceptable and not worth paying money for.

I'd rather have a 96kbps .mp3 of a good song from its original release than a poorly remastered "hi-fi" 192Khz 24-bit FLAC
Sorry you're deaf and dumb, but one day you'll be listening to a song and wonder why it sounds like shit when you remember it used to sound good and you'll find out it's a remaster. When that happens try to remember we warned you.

3. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=guvPSEVhaiM
a cover 100x more soulful than any other version. just a full 12-string with a fitting sorrowful choir of three. almost put nick drake's parasite here as his marvelous guitar work emulates the fullness of a 12-string (not to mention the similar melancholy tone), but everybody's talkin' fits my mood for tonight.
2. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wNM9FlgHBo8
unabashedly joyful. the sound of what people conceive their childhood innocence must have been. vocal harmonies introducing a hypnotic-lullaby chorus. a distant, echoing piano-vibraphone-organ mix hinting at something dark that only comes through in the instrumental bridge. however, but the electric fuzz of the guitar and innocent rhythm of the maracas see you through the light woe to a nostalgically joyful resolution
1. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KXUJMaYzh6U
grit. the roar of a car's engine on a sweltering day. the freedom and sunshine upon your soul. it truly is alright, in fact, it's a gas. warbling, shouting guitars of richards and jones twisting together in an unabashedly wild dance, sometimes mingling with the booming piano of hopkins (who unfortunately gets mixed out quite a bit during this era of the stones). what this song does excellently is build up toward climaxes. it builds up to the vocal harmonies, to the subtle escape from the surrounding fuzz, to the trumpets, to the jingling outro. if the warm tears of happiness was a song, it'd be this one

There's funk, synths, soul crooning, ambient, the motorik, Iggy, Eno, and a pervasive dissociative alienation that clocked postpunk right out of the gate. Frankly I think Throbbing Gristle and Joy Division learned a lot from the quasi cinematic moodiness of it all. Not to mention, this is basically the template for Phil Collins gated drum sound

In retrospect, its most every major pop development of the 80's in 1977. Whether it sounds good doesn't matter, that's enough to make it worth talking about

posts.com: Herr Weingartner does not confine himself to speaking of the eccentricities of conductors, but has a good deal to say about the unpleasantness which the post of opera-conductor in Germany generally involves. Nor is he silent as to the tricks which, Eulenspiegel-like, he has himself played off upon the public and critics. He amusingly relates that some ten years ago he and his friend Alfred Reisenauer had agreed to play Liszt's Symphonic Poem "Die Ideale" and his "Faust" Symphony, arranged for two pianofortes, at a Concert of the Cassel Wagner Society. The committee begged that they would not introduce two compositions of the "horrible" Liszt, as this would drive the public away. They stuck to their resolution, played both works, but announced "Die Ideale" as a "Fantasia for two pianofortes, by Franz Schubert (after the 'Unfinished' Symphony, the master's last work)," which naturally did not exist. It was most warmly received by the public, and was generally spoken of by the press as a "pearl of Schubertian melody." Only one of the critics discovered in it an element which was strange to and far-fetched for the lyrical Schubert. The "Faust" Symphony, on the other hand, was roundly abused.

>Hegel is a matter of taste.… And not only of German but of European taste!… A taste which Wagner understood!—which he felt equal to! which he has immortalised!—All he did was to apply it to music—he invented a style for himself, which might mean an “infinity of things,”—he was Hegel's heir.… Music as “Idea.”—

>The Ring itself is a post-Hegelian work. In the descent into Nibelheim, Wagner gives us an image of industrial capitalism that says more than a thousand pages of Karl Marx. In the character of Wotan he presents a brilliant summary of the vision underlying Hegel's political philosophy. And in the drama of Siegfried and Brünnhilde he unfolds an epitome of the idealist philosophy of self-knowledge.
>Looking back on this episode in cultural history, we see that Wagner was the true voice in music of Hegelian idealism. But he added a dimension that was entirely his own.

>Hegelian contradiction forms the material of Wotan’s Walküre monologue – better, dialectical self-dialogue. Negation of Wotan’s original political intent, a monarchical state under rule of law, is revealed as implicit in that state’s founding, yet revelation may only, in Hegelian spirit, come historically, contradictions having became apparent. “The owl of Minerva only takes flight at the onset of dusk,” that Dämmerung prophetic of Götterdämmerung itself (“die Eule der Minerva beginnt erst mit der einbrechenden Dämmerung ihren Flug,” Hegel, 7:28). I've lived in both countries, in a fairly large city in both countries, and dressing like a weirdo/being part of a subgroup is way more acceptable in the US, at least from my experience. When I was growing up in the UK, everyone who dressed in any kind of alternative fashion whatsoever got called catch all terms "mosher" or "greebo", even if that alternative subculture didn't actually have anything to do moshing. People are way less judgy in the US and are less likely to comment on your appearance, at least in metropolitan areas. Malls here straight up have half a dozen alternative clothing stores, which just wasn't a thing where I was from in the UK, hence the existence of the term "Mall Goth". If you dressed like that in the middle of the religious deep south it would probably be different story though, but that's not where I live.

>>115008128
It's a zeuhl chart. Zeuhl is a subgenre of prog that is characterized by operatic, booming vocals often in made up languages, aggressive, chaotic and frantic sounding composition similar to brutal prog and free jazz. Personally, I love zeuhl and you should take a listen to a bunch of these albums. If you decide to take a listen, you gotta listen to MAGMA (at least Mekanik Destruktiw Kommandoh), Koenji Hyakkei, Ruins, ZAO, Corima, eX-Girl, Amygdala and Eskaton. Have fun.

>essehntiaahl zund (essential)
>amahteuhr zund (amateur)

>zeuhl ubehr maniaahk zund (zeuhl uber maniac)

>Both Coltrane and Vander sound like shamans channeling something otherworldly through their music
You should listen to Leon Thomas. He does the vocals on Pharoah Sander's Karma, and his voice as this weird vibrating/undulating texture that's similar to Coltrane's sax playing. It really sounds like the kind of otherworldly shamanic vibe you describe, but with some funky rhythms.

There are a fuckton of people playing different instruments and genres that were inspired by Trane, but Magma is easily one of the best ones. Umbrella term and not really a subgenre just to describe bands that are on the more extreme end of prog rock without really being metal. Common elements is technicality brought to its breaking point, influences from the more avant-garde and chaotic side of jazz, little to no "classical" influences, lots of crossover with noise rock, post-hardcore and/or extreme metal, simultaneously minimalist and maximalist, dissonant, etc.
Also a lot of brutal prog falls under/is heavily influenced by Magma, not because Magma is brutal prog but the first brutal prog bands were all extreme variants of zeuhl.

>>115048336
>it's a specific musical tradition
Not really? Brutal prog isn't a specific sound or a genre; it's a catch-all for avant-prog bands that draw more from extreme and intense styles of music.

Brutal prog wasn't even coined until the early 2000s, with that general catch-all definition, and a lot of the 1980s and 1990s stuff was retroactively labeled brutal prog (when originally it was just thrown under the vague avant-prog umbrella with modifiers like avant-jazz and noise rock thrown in).
It's only a "specific music tradition" in Japan where a lot of brutal prog there share a lot of the same roots and newer Japanese brutal prog bands are influenced by older Japanese brutal prog bands; brutal prog's a lot more over the place and disconnected from being a set-in-stone style in the West.

>though I agree it's not a subgenre of progressive rock
No, but it's a branch within progressive rock, not its own unique identity
>because of the fact they have very different origins
The first brutal prog bands entirely cited progressive rock as their biggest influences mate, it's not a bunch of completely unrelated bands that were lumped in with prog rock based on similarities; talk to pioneers like Yoshida (Ruins) and his favourite bands were Gentle Giant and Magma and he doesn't even cite anything outside of 1970s prog as an influence. He does say punk was an influence but he doesn't even name any bands, like he wasn't really influenced by punk really but moreso just wanted to make something as intense as punk.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>115049206
>Not really? Brutal prog isn't a specific sound or a genre
It is. It's the musical tradition that developed out of Ruins and similar bands.

>it's a catch-all for avant-prog bands that draw more from extreme and intense styles of music
If that's how you are using the term you are using it wrong.

>Brutal prog wasn't even coined until the early 2000s
Yeah, so what? Brutal prog didn't grow in popularity beyond a few key bands until the late 90s. Lots of genres are defined this way.

>a lot of the 1980s and 1990s stuff was retroactively labeled brutal prog
Almost all early examples of genres are retroactively labeled as their established genres. Public Image Ltd weren't called post-punk when they recorded their debut, for example, that label came later, but we wouldn't say post-punk isn't a genre because of this.

>brutal prog's a lot more over the place and disconnected from being a set-in-stone style in the West
That's not true, the western bands also work in the tradition of the japanese bands. Yowie started as a Ruins copy, Flying Luttenbachers took from Naked City and Ruins (Naked City introduced Ruins in the US), Pak were also a Ruins copy except in english, and so on.

>No, but it's a branch within progressive rock
It developed independently from progressive rock.

>The first brutal prog bands entirely cited progressive rock as their biggest influences mate
Sure they did, but their sound was way different. The first progressive rock bands cited classical composers as their biggest influences, but that doesn't mean progressive rock is a classical subgenre.

>He does say punk was an influence but he doesn't even name any bands
He literally played in literal punk bands before he gradually started moving towards the proggier stuff. And it even shows in his earlier Ruins releases, those are also very strongly influenced by punk.

>he wasn't really influenced by punk
You are way off. Listen to 80s Ruins again.

This might not be the right place to request this, but since this is a Share thread, I thought I would ask for people's help.

I'm looking for a download of a compilation bootleg called The Birth of Grateful Dead. (NOT to be confused with the official release entitled Birth of The Dead)
This came out in the early 1990s on the "Unbelievable Music" label with the number UM 033.
It has early studio recordings from 1966, I believe. I don't know if they were The Grateful Dead yet, or still The Warlocks. Also on this bootleg is an outtake from AOXOMOXOA called "The Grateful Dead Meets The Mothers of Invention" (On other studio bootlegs, I've seen this piece under the title Barbed Wire Whipping Party. It's basically a recording of the band huffing nitrus oxide while a group of people in the background chant "Give me my meat") It also has Micky's "Rap" version of Fire On The Mountain, a rather nice studio version of Mason's Children, and one of the few and rare Lovelight performances where Janis Joplin joins Pig Pen.
Any help in finding a download would be appreciated.
I have a friend who think they don't like The Grateful Dead because they've met nothing but the stereotypical "Drop LSD and save the world" type of head, and thinks all Grateful Dead are Workingman's Dead and American Beauty, and I just KNOW that if they heard this bootleg, they would instantly change their mind.

Again, any help in tracking down a download would be appreciated.

Thanks in advance.

Jefferson Airplane Takes Off (Original vinyl FIRST PRESSING)
>Proto-Psychedelic rock and roll
>Haight-Asbury pre-Hippy music
>Your great grandparents dropped LSD to this when it was still legal
>NO GRACE SLICK
Originally, there was only a pressing of 500 copies of this album, as RCA Records wanted to jump on the hipie band wagon, but didn't think Jefferson Airplane would be known outside of San Francisco.

They lyrics to Let Me In are different than on later pressings, (The original version would later reappear on a Jefferson Airplane compilation in the late 1980s Jefferson Airplane Loves You) and Running Around was pulled due to it's controversial lyrics, but would later end up reissued on a compilation called Early Flight.

Listened to object oriented abstraction, Cheap Vacation and null pointer exception. Love the sampling, object oriented abstraction has a very heavy Portishead feeling with the orchestra samples and Cheap Vacation gives echoes of Paul's Boutique with the laidback, wah-wah guitar riff and twang, but honestly the songs sound more like beats to rap on than full fleshed songs. I can see that you stay too much on the traditional side of beatmaking, in my opinion that kind of damages the songs. The ideas you have on those track give you a lot of directions of where to go, in terms of the sample collages you can make and how to play with different contrast of the samples, instead you stay with a simple structure that doesn't play with expectations or make interestings changes. >>115059777
>I put all of the other locations back.

Your problem is a known error with Reaper software that has been dealt in the forums for multiple years

This error happens because Reaper has to scan several sub-folders at once. The forums offer one solution that work 100% of the time:

1. Clean up your folder paths so that they're consolidated, or have Reaper scan them one at a time (i.e. remove all the paths, then scan them back in one by one).

2. Try this Win+R>regedit \HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE right-click New>Key name it VST locate the folder VST right-click New String Value name it VSTPluginsPath in the Value data field set the location of where you want all your VST's to installed at example C:\Program Files\Common Files\VST2. Keep in mind that when you install a new VST, not all installers will ask you where you want the VST dll file to be located sometimes you will have to locate it manually and cut&paste it to the correct location. If you have software hubs like Output or Softube or like that Amp Sim you may need to adjust the location there as well or perform a repair. Doing this will ensure that all VSTs are located under one folder and not scattered about all over your system.

Remember: there is nothing wrong with Reaper or the AMP Sim you purchased. I tried the demo and it works. It's that you are unable to use these softwares properly within the limits of your operating system.

Listened to the first four songs. This is an interesting evolution of your style, it merges the instrumentation and melodies of american Country music with the overblown, noisy Rock that you typically made in a very natural way. The ideas in every song don't feel repetitive or derivative of one another, the joyful Country piano and guitar riffs paired with the Noise Rock freakouts of The Charm of The Countryside works perfectly as an opener, Texas Candles reflects a more laidback sound with his tempo and slide guitar solos and A Small Man Named Wyoming follows the previous ideas named. A Sound Mirage is perhaps a song that doesn't fit a lot with the theme of the album. Recommended.

>What is their musics purpose? It's not something you can put on to enjoy.
>You put it on to feel tingle in your ears and feel like a twink?

not far off except for the twink part.
the problem with radiohead is that they didn't invent anything new besides a few timbre.

the most important thing they pulled into the mainstream was making a hook out of something that is definitely NOT a hook or not supposed to be a hook.

they got everyone addicted to little sounds and noises, rather than blunt choruses. You can even think of them as musicians trying to find the rarest chord progressions in pop music and writing something around it. this process was achieved by being inspired by neil young, who writes like this, miles davis, who stumbles onto ideas by riffing, and thom yorke being egotistical.

that's it, the highlight of radiohead songs isn't any particular part or melody or harmony, but a particular itch that you get from hearing the way something is put or heard. their conception of hooks just goes a little beyond what rock music had been about leading up to that point.

on the other hand they write a lot of very generic songs too. listen to the smile, theres no solos, no weird highlight moments, the songs are homogenous and their form is very predictable.

radiohead manages to be catchy without doing anything to make them catchy. they also never tolerate having a "boring" part in their songs. Their entire songs are engineered to be interesting in every moment, just like 80s pop.

posts.com:
Paul Simon [Columbia, 1972]
I've been saying nasty things about Simon since 1967, but this is the only thing in the universe to make me positively happy in the first two weeks of February 1972. I hope Art Garfunkel is gone for good--he always seemed so vestigial, but it's obvious now that two-part harmony crippled Simon's naturally agile singing and composing. And the words! This is a professional tour of Manhattan for youth culture grads, complete with Bella Abzug, hard rain, and people who steal your chow fong. The self-production is economical and lively, with the guitars of Jerry Hahn and Stefan Grossman and Airto Moreira's percussion especially inspired. William Carlos Williams after the repression: "Peace Like a River." A+
